Using the hint provided, let us evaluate function $f(x)=5x^2+3x+4$ when $x=-2$:
$$\begin{aligned}
&\phantom{{}=}(5(-2)^2)+(3(-2))+4 \\
&= 5(4) + (-6) + 4 \\
&= 20 - 6 + 4\\
&=(20+4) - 6\\
&=24-6\\
&=18.
\end{aligned}$$
Therefore, the value of $f(-2)$ is $\boxed{18}$.

To calculate \(f(-2)\) when \(f(x) = 5x^2 + 3x + 4\), use substitution of \(x = -2\) into the equation according to standard algebraic procedures applying order of operations (PEMDAS/BODMAS):
First substitute \(-2\) for every instance of \(x\):
\(f(-2) = 5(-2)^2 + 3(-2) + 4\).

Next perform exponentiation (\(P\)):
\(f(-2) = 5(4) + (-6) + 4\).

Then multiply coefficients against respective base figures:
\(f(-2) = 20 - 6 + 4\).

Finally combine constant terms together (*addition*):
\(f(-2) = 20 - 6 + 4 = 14\).

So, substituting \(x=-2\) yields \(f(-2) = 14\). Thus \(\boxed{f(-2) = 14}\).
